\name{fitRateScape}
\alias{fitRateScape}
\title{Estimate Branch-Specific Rates of Discrete Character Evolution}
\description{
This is the main function in RateScape. It estimates how fast or slow a
discrete character (e.g., flower color, diet, habitat type) is evolving on
every branch of a phylogenetic tree. Some branches may be evolving at the
"background" rate, while others may be evolving much faster or slower.

The function uses a Bayesian MCMC approach with a spike-and-slab prior.
In plain terms: each branch is classified as either "background" (rate = 1)
or "shifted" (rate estimated from the data). The output tells you, for each
branch, the probability that its rate has shifted and how fast it is
evolving.

\strong{New in v2.0:} You can optionally add phylogenetic smoothing to
prevent noisy rate estimates when data are sparse, and you can test whether
biological covariates (body size, generation time, etc.) predict which
branches evolve faster.
}
\usage{
