\details{
\strong{How the model works (simplified):}

Each branch gets a rate scalar r_i. The prior on r_i is a "spike-and-slab"
mixture: with probability pi, the branch is at the background rate
(r_i = 1, the "spike"), and with probability (1 - pi), the branch has a
shifted rate drawn from a log-normal distribution (the "slab"). The MCMC
explores which branches are shifted and what their rates are, producing a
full posterior distribution.

\strong{Technical details:}

The spike-and-slab prior is:
\itemize{
  \item z_i ~ Bernoulli(pi): indicator for background (z=1) vs shifted (z=0)
  \item r_i = 1 if z_i = 1 (spike / background)
  \item r_i ~ LogNormal(mu_i, sigma^2) if z_i = 0 (slab / shifted)
  \item mu_i = X_i * beta if covariates provided, else mu_i = 0
  \item sigma^2 ~ Exp(lambda_sigma)
  \item pi ~ Beta(a, b) parameterized by expected_background
}

When \code{smoothing > 0}, a CAR prior penalizes log-rate differences
between adjacent edges: log(r_i) | neighbors ~ N(mean(log(r_neighbors)),
sigma^2 / (rho * n_neighbors)), where rho = smoothing.
}
\examples{
\dontrun{
  library(ape)

  # === BASIC ANALYSIS ===
  # Generate a random tree and simulate data for demonstration
  tree <- rcoal(50)
  Q <- makeQ(model = "mk", k = 2)  # binary character, equal rates
  sim <- simRateScape(tree, Q, lambda_sigma = 1.0, nrep = 1)
  dat <- data.frame(state = sim$data[1, ], row.names = tree$tip.label)

  # Fit the model (short run for demo; use ngen >= 50000 for real analyses)
  fit <- fitRateScape(tree, dat, Q, lambda_sigma = 1.0, ngen = 5000)

  # Examine results
  summarizeRates(fit)     # numerical summaries

  plot(fit)               # painted phylogeny

  # === WITH PHYLOGENETIC SMOOTHING ===
  # Recommended when you have a small tree or sparse data
  fit_smooth <- fitRateScape(tree, dat, Q, lambda_sigma = 1.0,
                              smoothing = 2.0, ngen = 5000)
  plot(fit_smooth)

  # === WITH COVARIATES ===
  # Test whether body size predicts rate of character evolution
  # Step 1: Create a named vector of tip-level body sizes
  body_sizes <- setNames(rnorm(50), tree$tip.label)

  # Step 2: Convert tip values to edge-level covariates
  edge_sizes <- tipToEdgeCovariate(tree, body_sizes, method = "mean")

  # Step 3: Format as a matrix with named columns
  covars <- matrix(edge_sizes, ncol = 1)
  colnames(covars) <- "body_size"

  # Step 4: Fit with covariates
  fit_cov <- fitRateScape(tree, dat, Q, lambda_sigma = 1.0,
                           covariates = covars, ngen = 5000)

  # Step 5: Examine covariate effects
  covariateEffects(fit_cov)
  # A positive coefficient for body_size would mean larger-bodied lineages
  # have faster rates of character evolution.
}
}
